"Saeed F., Hagemann S., Jacob D.","Impact of irrigation on the South Asian summer monsoon",2009,"Geophysical Research Letters","36","20", L20711,"","",,,10.1029/2009GL040625,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-72149128903&partnerID=40&md5=b98c68dcca7f546218be08d68abdec8d","Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstrasse 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany","Saeed, F., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstrasse 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Hagemann, S., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstrasse 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany; Jacob, D., Max Planck Institute for Meteorology, Bundesstrasse 53, D-20146 Hamburg, Germany","The Indian subcontinent is one of the most intensely irrigated regions of the world and state of the art climate models do not account for the representation of irrigation. Sensitivity studies with the regional climate model REMO show distinct feedbacks between the simulation of the monsoon circulation with and without irrigation processes. We find that the temperature and mean sea level pressure, where the standard REMO version without irrigation shows a significant bias over the areas of Indus basin, is highly sensitive to the water used for irrigation. In our sensitivity test we find that removal of this bias has caused less differential heating between land and sea masses. This in turns reduces the westerlies entering into land from Arabian Sea, hence creating conditions favorable for currents from Bay of Bengal to intrude deep into western India and Pakistan that have been unrealistically suppressed before. We conclude that the representation of irrigated water is unavoidable for realistic simulation of south Asian summer monsoon and its response under global warming. Copyright 2009 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Arabian Sea; Asian summer monsoons; Bay of Bengal; Climate model; Differential heating; Highly sensitive; Mean sea level pressures; Monsoon circulations; Pakistan; Realistic simulation; Regional climate models; Sensitivity studies; Sensitivity tests; State of the art; Global warming; Sea level; Simulators; Irrigation; climate feedback; climate modeling; global warming; irrigation system; nature-society relations; oceanic current; regional climate; sea level pressure; sensitivity analysis; water use; westerly; Arabian Sea; Asia; Bay of Bengal; Eurasia; Indian Ocean; Pakistan; South Asia",,,,,,"Ashfaq, M., Suppression of South Asian summer monsoon precipitation in the 21st century (2009) Geophys. Res. Lett., 36, pp. L01704. , doi:10.1029/2008GL036500; Cadet, D., Meteorology of the Indian summer monsoon (1979) Nature, 279, pp. 761-767. , doi:10.1038/279761a0; De Rosnay, P., Integrated parameterization of irrigation in the land surface model ORCHIDEE: Validation over Indian Peninsula (2003) Geophys. Res. Lett., 30 (19), p. 1986. , doi:10.1029/2003GL018024; Douglas, E.M., Changes in moisture and energy fluxes due to agricultural land use and irrigation in the Indian Monsoon Belt (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett., 33, pp. L14403. , doi:10.1029/2006GL026550; Douglas, E.M., The impact of agricultural intensification and irrigation on land-atmosphere interactions and Indian monsoon precipitation-A mesoscale modeling perspective (2009) Global Planet. Change, 67, pp. 117-128. , doi:10.1016/j.gloplacha.2008.12.007; Hagemann, S., (1999) Derivation of Global GCM Boundary Conditions from 1 Km Land Use Satellite Data, 34p. , Rep. 289, Max Planck Inst. Meteorol., Hamburg, Germany; Jacob, D., A note to the simulation of the annual and inter-annual variability of the water budget over the Baltic Sea drainage basin (2001) Meteorology and Atmospheric Physics, 77 (1-4), pp. 61-73. , DOI 10.1007/s007030170017; Jacob, D., Barring, L., Christensen, O.B., Christensen, J.H., De Castro, M., Deque, M., Giorgi, F., Van Den Hurk, B., An inter-comparison of regional climate models for Europe: Model performance in present-day climate (2007) Climatic Change, 81 (SUPPL. 1), pp. 31-52. , DOI 10.1007/s1058